# {{law}} A written command, issued by a judge, requiring whomever it is served upon to do whatever the order says, under penalty of being held in [[contempt of court]].
#:'''1920''' ''The Reds were raising an awful howl. Andrews, the lawyer, had succeeded in getting a '''court order''' to see the arrested men, and of course the prisoners had all declared that the case was a put-up job.'' — Upton Sinclair, ''100%: The Story of a Patriot'', [http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/ot2www-pubeng?specfile=/texts/english/modeng/publicsearch/modengpub.o2w&act=surround&offset=581099048&tag=Sinclair,+Upton,+1878-1968:+100%:+The+Story+of+a+Patriot,+1920&query=court+order&id=SinStor §54.]